repo.description: The most widely used Python to C compiler
repo.name: cython

body:
**Note:** draft PR - I'm submitting it mainly to see the test results. I don't know whether it's the approach we want to take or not yet. I don't think it's worth reviewing until we've decided if we want it.

On the basis that PEP563 looks unlikely to be the annotation behaviour that Python uses in future, this PR:
* restores the old (annotations evaluated when function/class is created) behaviour
* Fixes a few some scoping issues with the old behaviour
* Supports PEP563 (annotations as strings) with `from __future__ import annotations`
(i.e. it's as close as possible to what Python currently does)

commit.message:
PEP563 style annotations

These are introduced using
from __future__ import annotations
as in Python.

To support them there's some general changes to how annotations
are handled, mainly a new "AnnotationNode" class, which separates
out the main uses of annotations within Cython so that they
don't interfere with each other.

There's also some of the changes from PR#3163 to help the
tests in embedsignature pass when binding=True:
 * mostly adding empty analyse_types to some coercionnodes
 * also ensuring stuff is evaluated in the correct scope (for
 old non-PEP563 annotations)
I think a few further changes will be needed to embedsignature
to ensure it passes with binding=True - these will come
separately

Some Python versioning issues

Python2 and string types is different
from __future__ import annotations doesn't work before Python 3.7
 (for pure Python mode tests)
Seems to work on basic test-cases

Better handling of c-types

Passes tests with "annot" in anyway

Move setting of subexprs much earlier

Because creation of scopes was causing problems if the
annotations were later dropped
